{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3127524,"name":"Brendan R.","username":"Braykoff","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/braykoff/{size}/204536_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-16T18:14:14.357Z","cooked":"

We recently updated our robot to the 2023 version of the RoboRio, which uses NetworkTables 4.0. We have updated the WPI tools on our computers as well. When we open ‘Glass’ (the dashboard used to view NetworkTables), it will not connect.

We set the client to NetworkTables4.0, enter the team number, and connect (the port number is the default). It connects momentarily, and immediately disconnects, saying the ‘connection was closed by the remote end’, This also occurs while using the IP address (10.TE.AM.2 notation).

No other NetworkTables programs (like SYSid, Shuffleboard) work.

I think it may have something to do with the ‘Network Identity’ field in Glass, I have no idea what this is/have never seen it before. It’s set to the default value (‘glass’), does this need to be changed?

Do you have any firewall or proxy software installed on your machine? NetworkTables uses a HTTP-based WebSockets connection and so an invasive firewall/proxy might be interfering with its attempts to connect.

Just to confirm, you are running 2023 robot code?

Does connecting with the NT3 protocol in glass work?

Braykoff:

We do have a firewall, but when prompted we allowed the connection.

What specific firewall? Windows firewall or something 3rd party? I’m wondering if the firewall “allowed” the connection but is still MITM’ing a HTTP proxy which is causing the issue (the NT4 HTTP client is very basic and isn’t going to understand proxy redirects or similar). Maybe try completely disabling the firewall?
